  "id": "bone-tumors-8cdf21",
  "title": "Bone Tumors - Differential Diagnosis",
  "source": "bone-tumors.html",
  "blocks": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Systematic approach to bone lesions: zone of transition, periosteal reaction, cortex, matrix, location, and multiplicity."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Source: Radiology Assistant \"Bone tumors - Differential diagnosis\". Images embedded locally."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Systematic Approach"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Start with patient age, lesion location (epiphysis/metaphysis/diaphysis, axial vs appendicular), and the most aggressive imaging feature."
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "assetId": "asset_8939df5fb6",
      "alt": "Bone tumor overview"
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "assetId": "asset_c0fed1a750",
      "alt": "Three-question approach"
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "assetId": "asset_33b379636f",
      "alt": "Approach summary"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Zone of Transition"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Narrow zone suggests slow growth/benign; wide or ill-defined transition suggests aggressive or malignant process (including infection or EG)."
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "assetId": "asset_fffa81d29d",
      "alt": "Narrow zone key points"
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "assetId": "asset_94d8c227eb",
      "alt": "Narrow zone examples: NOF, SBC, ABC"
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "assetId": "asset_a36e8aa4ba",
      "alt": "Metastatic lesions illustration"
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "assetId": "asset_0f3ab65138",
      "alt": "Wide zone indicates aggressiveness"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Periosteal Reaction"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Smooth, uninterrupted periosteal reaction is typically benign/stress/healing; aggressive patterns include lamellated, spiculated, or Codman triangle."
    },
    {
